<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900710-0081</DOCNO><DOCID>900710-0081.</DOCID><HL>   Computer Hackers   Plead Guilty in Case   Involving BellSouth</HL><DATE>07/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   BLS</CO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><LP>   ATLANTA -- Three men, part of a closely knit group ofcomputer hackers calling themselves the Legion of Doom,pleaded guilty to conspiring to defraud BellSouth Corp. ofcomputer information.   In February, the three men, Franklin E. Darden Jr., 24years old, of Norcross, Ga.; Adam E. Grant, 22, and Robert J.Riggs, 22, both of Atlanta, were indicted as participants inan alleged scheme to disrupt telephone service in theSoutheast.</LP><TEXT>   BellSouth, through two subsidiaries, oversees phoneservice in Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia, Tennessee,Kentucky, Louisiana, Florida and the Carolinas.   Yesterday, Mr. Darden and Mr. Riggs each pleaded guilty toone count of conspiring to commit computer fraud. Both face amaximum penalty of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.Mr. Grant pleaded guilty to possessing 15 or more devicesthat provided access to BellSouth computers with intent tocommit fraud. He faces up to 10 years in prison as well as a$250,000 fine.   Neither Mr. Riggs nor Mr. Grant could be reached forcomment. Mr. Darden said he had agreed to cooperate withBellSouth in helping to secure the company's computersystems. Acknowledging that he was &quot;more or less a hacker,&quot;Mr. Darden said his actions were simply a hobby at first. &quot;Ihope anybody that's hacking out there now hears this andstops,&quot; he added. Sentencing for all three men is set forSept. 14.   A hacker is a person who attempts to gain unauthorizedaccess to computer files in various systems.   The U.S. attorney in Atlanta, Joe Whitley, said yesterdaythat the three individuals belonged to the so-called Legionof Doom, a cadre of 15 computer hackers in Georgia, Texas,Michigan, Illinois, Florida, New York and other states.   Mr. Whitley said the group disrupted thetelecommunications industry, monitored private telephonelines, stole proprietary information, stole and modifiedcredit information, fraudulently obtained property fromvarious companies, and disseminated information that allowedother computer hackers to enter BellSouth and other computersystems.</TEXT></DOC>